This song is cursed.

When I first saw this song here, on youtube, the first comment that was in a comment section was a guy telling that he got into a car accident listening to this song. And somehow this exact comment got stuck into my head. Every time i heard this song in my playlist, even not on a youtube, i always remembered this exact comment. Scary, kinda.

Months go by, I start to listen to this song much fewer.

At some day my father was driving me on a pretty long roadtrip. I decided to turn on my entire playlist mixed. At some moment of it, we got stuck in a huge traffic jam. We spent there for something about an hour. And when we were about to finally leave it, this song started to play. I even thought "what can go wrong, we're on an empty road already". Well, basically it was truth - the road was literally empty, the closest car in front of us was something about 100-200 meters away.

The song is about to end, the last minute of it plays. We have to stop on a pedestrian crossing. We stayed there for about 10 seconds, people go by, the traffic light is red.
And then a Renault Logan JUST RAMS us, almost on a full speed. Then i realised that what I said at the beginning is. fckng. truth.

The guy who rammed into us said that he "didn't see the traffic light". No one got hurt, tho.

@poggy I hope things get better for you, I really empathise with the last sentance. I'm not sure what yours are like, but mine go against all my morals and make me feel like I am the worst possible thing that can exist, and make me feel like there's something fundamentally wrong with me, which is extremely hard to just accept and move on from. During the worst of it for me, November and October of 2020, it felt like I was being consumed by these thoughts. I couldn't do anything I wanted to do in fear of triggering the thoughts and considering the smallest, most nonsensical things triggered them it was impacting my life greatly. Once I remember sitting in my kitchen eating breakfast, thinking of snowy trees, and somehow I ended up being attacked by intrusive thoughts?? By trees?? Fortunately though, I have found things are getting better, and I've found ways to help me manage them. They're most likely never going to completely go away for me, and it's still impacting my life, but wayyy less severely and less often too. If you'd like, I can share how I handle them, though they're only what's been working for me personally and honestly have their fair share of issues, but I wouldn't mind if you feel it might help :)

It's wise to not let something as inconsequential as that impede your day, which is why I don't. I let them come and go like an ocean breeze, actively choosing not to dwell on the "bad" thoughts just because they stick out.

It is only when you act on them, that they become real, and harmful.

hello, miss Jvnko,

everything started some months ago. i found your channel through the recommendations of a "friend" of mine. at first, i didnt like your music. but recently i decided to listen to it yet again. and so, id like to say that, dear god, your style is so unique. music is an important part of my life. ive used it as a coping mechanism for years. i know many musicians. but ive NEVER seen someone like you.

how could I describe it?... that depends. every song of yours gives off different vibes for me. for example, "pretty cvnt" makes me kind of desperately angry. i have anger issues since I was a child and it was always kind of in controllable so i like the "rawness" of it.

i also relate to " dysphoria". i used to listen to it a lot when i came out as trans to some people, because that song retracts what i and many other people feel. it's like therapy.
additionally, i haven't talked about this until now, but the thing is that I love the fact trans artists like you are getting recognition.

you're also a big inspiration of mine. i plan to make music soon and, if i do that, ill make sure to give you credits for that. sorry if this comment is too cheesy or something, but yes, you're really good at what you do.

thank you for making such meaningful and deep music for us.

commentText: cool song but can someone explain why one might find this song sad or depressive? i see alot of comments about that but I dont feel the song is at all like that.

replies.commentText: cool song but can someone explain why one might find this song sad or depressive? i see alot of comments about that but I dont feel the song is at all like that.

Its the dichotomy of soothing pads and aggressive breaks that sort of stands out to people as both calming and intense at the same time. I think a lot of people compare this feeling to a lot of stress in their personal lives; I know Ive had many sleepless nights just melancholically thinking about my life, while at the same time there is some comfort to be had there, sitting alone and feeling bad for oneself. Its hard to explain unless youve experienced it, but its definitely real...

I mean lets be honest, 90% of the people who click a title like this are/were depressed at some point in their lives. All that paired with the fact the title literally refers to suicide, and the thumbnail/track art is a girl with a gun to her head. Youve planted the idea of depression in people's heads so when theyre listening, theyre more likely to interpret it as "depression music"; in the same way that some music used in horror films are actually quite calming outside the context of a horror scene, but within that horror context is interpretted by a viewer as unnerving.

Lots of thoughts for one comment, thats kind of my bad. I hope you got something out of it anyways.
@taggerung thanks for your comment, it explains alot. i appreciate the time you took to write it

I kinda realize today that this song reminded me of a track from Fire Emblem: Fates called Desire Below. It has reminded me of other tracks in other games, but this particular one struck me more because of the dreamlike qualities of the Calm version, and the energetic feel of the Flow version; and how this song has mixed those two features together (in my mind at least). This song, however, gets incredibly more chaotic as time goes on until eventually it all ceases to exist and we are left in calmness. It must have taken a lot of effort to make everything seem nostalgic as if you've heard it somewhere before. In most cases, it's a case of coincidence, but there might be some stark similarities here and there to other songs.

What made me want to write this comment, however, is the absolute chaos that this song goes in and out of, and how it affects that nostalgia. About halfway into the song (about where there are Japanese girls saying some phrase that I don't know about since I don't know Japanese), the same beats and melodies that were already used in the first half are used again, and upon going beyond the calming nature of the song, it became more sinister as I realise that I'm falling down a pit of nostalgia. I'm not sure how to describe it, but it felt like a bunch of flowing colours were everywhere, the most prominent being magenta and some bluish-green colour. I could vaguely make out actual past memories from within the colours, but ultimately I felt like I was getting lost, falling down what seemed like a bottomless pit. The future and present seemed to have no meaning anymore within that realm and all I could think down there was looking back and grabbing into the past. In the bits of calm, they took me back to the track I mentioned earlier, which was apparently also called Sea of Aspiration. It also described what I felt during those calm moments, where I was swimming in an endless sea of my aspirations and responsibilities in my life. When the chaos comes into the mix, I get pulled back down into that pit. I guess this song to me, is a song of escapism and letting go of all of what's in the present and future, to get lost in the past.

But why have I described this pit of nostalgia as sinister? Well, it's because of the name of the song. This song isn't just about escapism from the present, it's also about escapism from the physical world. The pit of nostalgia is a way to tie space and time together, giving people who are lost in the past a way to regain their past livelihoods, death in the present. This song is the equivalent of a siren, giving those who tread too far a desire or lust that would ultimately result in their lives taken just to feed the siren. This song is personified through its title. This song is the title. It wants you, the listener, to do it. Honestly, that may be the most beautiful and terrifying part at the same time.

Yeah, if you're wondering/don't know, that bassline can be more specifically called an acid bassline. It comes from the roots of Electronic music and the unique squelchy sound of the Roland TR-303 which had a resonant filter that could squelch unlike anything heard before. It's been used in what's called Acid House since it was first track of it's genre was created in 1987. It is a sound that defined electronic music. And even since it's age of fame has passed, people still use the sound to give that famous squelchy This sound which is so deeply engrained in Electronic Music's history.
Sorry for the slight history lesson (I did research myself in this :p ), but if you noticed it and want to hear more I recommend that you do, the music really is something you can't find anywhere else. I'd probably start with Phuture - Acid Trax, the first Acid house song to exist, the lineage of electronic music is a rich one, history wise and sound wise.
And If you already knew this, well now you know more.

I wrote a poem while listening to this:


The bass is heavy in the atmosphere
I can feel it in my skin
I can feel it every time i breath in
Circuit board dust and plastic beads off the shores of
Every—single—fucking—beach
Undertones of the ocean oil staying in my machine mind
A nice sip of rejuvenation to start off your day!
Instance start accelerate go stop red yellow blue squares that pattern together and make a smiling united hell
Exes of havoc flashes and strobe light refinery hacks inside a life that wasn’t what it was when I was young
The flag the flag it stands in front like a bastardized version of liberty
Off the 405 like a vendetta of misery against nature itself
Smile it’s your birthday
Smile it’s your number 6c 6f 76 65
That’s who you are
You fucking live in this identity
You fuck to reproduce our humanity
You have nothing more than just a slip and card to determine your role in this slice of life rollercoaster yeehaw and frenzied panic attack lifeless bag of shackles that guzzles down a dump truck of continuous exhaust
It’s what we dream of when our days are at their end
Static static my heart sends off in erratic lashes of modern joy
In grueling black water behind alleyways of death
Where we fight in plastic bag oil fuel blood
In the gasoline fire
Where hands over mouth telling me it’s okay in dark cars and shuttered maze
It’s so wrong but it feels so right
Brother and sister fuck fight
Baby your mother died so you could feel my cancerous light
Question riddle and gangrene peddlers I stand off with in cars side by side
Can I look into your life
Can I look into your neurons and see where you lie
To yourself and ask the question it hides hides and hides ahah it hides in layers of fucking trash
Like our parks and our sacred land
On death beds of men and women raped and killed
Forget in exponential haste
You fucking moron
You fucking regrettable instance of existence that ties a noose around a flightless neck
Tearing the skin to the bone
That’s me in that car listening to nothing
Listening to the lights flash in sync with the modem that gives me some sort of secrecy to a world that listens too closely to how I feel
That touches me and seduces me with every aspect of who I am
Must I relate in every aspect of who you are


The bicycle of the mind is a fucking torture device when you bend it to the mercy of a gun
And suck the barrel like a ignited cigar
ash filling your throat

" my cousin is in the hospital"
"Oh, I hope they are ok. What happened to them?"

The song was... enjoyable but unengaging. It felt very uninspired and sorta like it was just... making the beats, there was no heart in it. Sounded a lot like Orbital's stuff with the vocal sampling and ambiance and Squarepusher in Hard Normal Daddy with the drum kits and other instrumentation used, which are both great artists, but this just felt like a weird amalgam of the two and didn't feel like something new, at least to me. My advice would probably be to lean into something new. I like the aesthetic and the sorta... there's a lot of potential, but I think leaning into an Eastern vibe or having more unique samples like the sorta schoolgirl Japanese voice used at the transition in 3:22, just creating something that has a discernable audio "signature" that makes it Sewerslvt and not just like... a longer Squarepusher track with more breaks. That's just my input, though. I appreciate the tunes, keep it up..!

I think the most important thing to remember is that the internet isn’t a box you shout into and it shouts back at you.

It’s a place where you can read the writings of millions of individual being with pasts, presents, and futures.

Really, that’s important for ANY interaction, but when everyone is just a username, or worse, just another Anon, it gets really easy to reduce everyone into a cacophony.

You can’t do that all the time, though. If you try to process the individuality of a crowd, you’ll paralyze yourself. Just do a few times a day.

If you believe you are a sovereign will, capable of independent thought and action, they extend that belief to the rest of us. If you believe we are social creatures who can co-operate and create, but can also be manipulated and mislead, then don’t let your ego blind you to being just like us.

I personally think that the latter is more true, but believing the former is more functional.

Anyway, I think I found my late night browsing music. This stuff isn’t nostalgic for me, but it’s a very novel sound. And hey, it’s either novelty or purpose!
